Package lab7

Class AirportLog

java.lang.Object
lab7.AirportLog
public class AirportLog extends Object
The AirportLog class is designed to manage a collection of Airport objects. It allows the addition and retrieval of Airport instances, enabling the management of multiple airports in a structured manner.

This class is useful in scenarios where there is a need to keep track of a list of airports, such as in airline management systems, airport network analysis, or for aggregating airport information.

  • Field Details

    • name

      private String name
      The name of the AirportLog. This field typically represents the identifier or descriptive title of the AirportLog instance. It can be used to differentiate between different AirportLog instances in a system that manages multiple sets of airports.

    • airports

      private ArrayList<Airport> airports
      A list of Airport objects managed by this AirportLog. This ArrayList stores Airport instances, providing a mechanism to handle multiple airports in an organized manner. The list supports operations like adding new airports, searching for specific airports, and iterating over all airports for display or processing purposes.

  • Constructor Details

    • AirportLog

      public AirportLog()
      Constructs a new AirportLog object with a default name and an empty list of airports. The default name is set to "Unknown", and the airports list is initialized as an empty ArrayList.

      Note: While this AirportLog instance owns the list (ArrayList) that contains the Airport objects, it does not own the actual Airport objects themselves. The Airport objects may exist independently of the AirportLog and can be shared across different AirportLog instances or other parts of the application. This design choice allows for flexible management of Airport objects without strict ownership and lifecycle coupling to the AirportLog instance.

    • AirportLog

      public AirportLog(String name, ArrayList<Airport> initialAirports)
      Constructs a new AirportLog object with a specified name and a list of initial airports. This constructor allows for the creation of an AirportLog with a custom name and a predefined collection of Airport objects.
      Parameters:
      name - The name to be assigned to this AirportLog. This name is used to identify the log and can represent its purpose or the collection of airports it contains.
      initialAirports - An ArrayList of Airport objects that will be initially contained in the log. This list is copied into the AirportLog, ensuring that the original list provided to the constructor remains unchanged and separate from the log's list.

      Note: The provided ArrayList of Airport objects is copied into the AirportLog's internal list. This means the AirportLog will have its own separate copy of the list, but it does not create new copies of the Airport objects themselves. The same Airport instances are shared between the provided list and the AirportLog's internal list. Therefore, changes to the Airport objects in one list will be reflected in the other.

  • Method Details

    • addAirport

      public void addAirport(Airport airport)
      Adds an Airport object to the current collection of airports in this AirportLog. This method appends the specified Airport object to the end of the list managed by this AirportLog.
      Parameters:
      airport - The Airport object to be added to the log. It should be a non-null instance of the Airport class.

      Note: The added Airport object is not cloned or copied; the AirportLog will store a reference to the original Airport object. Therefore, any modifications made to the Airport object after it has been added to the log will be reflected within the log. This design allows for dynamic updates to the properties of airports within the log but requires careful management of Airport objects to avoid unintended side effects.

    • findAirport

      public AirportLog findAirport(String state, String country)
      Searches for and returns a new AirportLog containing all airports in the specified state and country. This method creates a new instance of AirportLog, which includes only those airports from the current log that match the given state and country criteria.
      Parameters:
      state - The state to match for the airports. It should be a non-null string representing the state in which the airport is located.
      country - The country to match for the airports. It should be a non-null string representing the country in which the airport is located.
      Returns:
      An AirportLog object containing the filtered list of airports. This new AirportLog has a name prefixed with "Filtered" followed by the name of the current log, and it includes only those airports that match the specified state and country. If no airports match the criteria, the returned AirportLog will contain an empty list of airports.

      Note: The returned AirportLog does not create new Airport instances but rather references the same Airport objects as in the original log. Any modifications made to the Airport objects in the returned log will be reflected in the original AirportLog and vice versa.

    • findAirport

      public Airport findAirport(int index)
      Retrieves an Airport object from the list based on its index. This method returns the Airport object located at the specified index in the AirportLog's list of airports. If the provided index is outside the bounds of the list, the method returns null.
      Parameters:
      index - The index of the Airport object to retrieve. It should be a non-negative integer.
      Returns:
      The Airport object at the specified index in the list of airports. If the index is invalid (i.e., less than 0 or greater than or equal to the size of the list), this method returns null.

      Note: The index is zero-based, meaning that the first element in the list is at index 0, the second element is at index 1, and so on. This method does not modify the list or the Airport objects within it.

    • size

      public int size()
      Returns the number of Airport objects currently stored in the AirportLog. This method provides a count of how many Airport instances are managed within the log.
      Returns:
      The number of Airport objects in the AirportLog. The value is a non-negative integer representing the total count of airports in the log.

    • getName

      public String getName()
      Returns the name of the AirportLog. This method retrieves the name assigned to the AirportLog instance, which is used to identify or describe the collection of airports it manages.
      Returns:
      The name of the AirportLog.

    • getAirports

      public ArrayList<Airport> getAirports()
      Returns the list of Airport objects managed by this AirportLog. This method provides access to the internal list of Airport instances. It's important to note that while the AirportLog owns the list itself, it does not own the individual Airport objects within the list. Any changes made to the returned Airport objects within the returned list will be reflected in the AirportLog instance.
      Returns:
      An ArrayList of Airport objects. Modifying the objects within it will affect the AirportLog's internal state.
